The data was donated in 2012 to UCI by a portuguese bank. It in most likely BPI given the size of the company.

bank = read.table("C:/Users/willi/Desktop/bank-additional/bank-additional/bank-additional-full.csv", sep=";",header=T)

Input variables: ###bank client data: 1 - age (numeric) 2 - job : type of job (categorical: ‘admin.’,‘blue-collar’,‘entrepreneur’,‘housemaid’,‘management’,‘retired’,‘self-employed’,‘services’,‘student’,‘technician’,‘unemployed’,‘unknown’) 3 - marital : marital status (categorical: ‘divorced’,‘married’,‘single’,‘unknown’; note: ‘divorced’ means divorced or widowed) 4 - education (categorical: ‘basic.4y’,‘basic.6y’,‘basic.9y’,‘high.school’,‘illiterate’,‘professional.course’,‘university.degree’,‘unknown’) 5 - default: has credit in default? (categorical: ‘no’,‘yes’,‘unknown’) 6 - housing: has housing loan? (categorical: ‘no’,‘yes’,‘unknown’) 7 - loan: has personal loan? (categorical: ‘no’,‘yes’,‘unknown’) ###related with the last contact of the current campaign: 8 - contact: contact communication type (categorical: ‘cellular’,‘telephone’) 9 - month: last contact month of year (categorical: ‘jan’, ‘feb’, ‘mar’, …, ‘nov’, ‘dec’) 10 - day_of_week: last contact day of the week (categorical: ‘mon’,‘tue’,‘wed’,‘thu’,‘fri’) 11 - duration: last contact duration, in seconds (numeric). Important note: this attribute highly affects the output target (e.g., if duration=0 then y=‘no’). Yet, the duration is not known before a call is performed. Also, after the end of the call y is obviously known. Thus, this input should only be included for benchmark purposes and should be discarded if the intention is to have a realistic predictive model. ###other attributes: 12 - campaign: number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client (numeric, includes last contact) 13 - pdays: number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (numeric; 999 means client was not previously contacted) 14 - previous: number of contacts performed before this campaign and for this client (numeric) 15 - poutcome: outcome of the previous marketing campaign (categorical: ‘failure’,‘nonexistent’,‘success’) ###social and economic context attributes 16 - emp.var.rate: employment variation rate - quarterly indicator (numeric) 17 - cons.price.idx: consumer price index - monthly indicator (numeric) 18 - cons.conf.idx: consumer confidence index - monthly indicator (numeric) 19 - euribor3m: euribor 3 month rate - daily indicator (numeric) 20 - nr.employed: number of employees - quarterly indicator (numeric)

Output variable (desired target): 21 - y - has the client subscribed a term deposit? (binary: ‘yes’,‘no’)

Data Cleaning

As mentioned above the duration is a very good predictor, but not important considering our business question. It is intuitive that if a call only last a few seconds there was probably no sale made. If a call last longer a sale is more likely to have been made, becuase more time is available to awnser the customers concerns before they invest.

table(bank[which(bank$duration < 38),]$y)
## 
##   no  yes 
## 2161    1

There would be no way to know the duration of the call before the call is made. The calls made with less than 4 seconds are deleted.

rows=row.names(bank[which(bank$duration < 4),])
rows=as.integer(rows)
bank = bank[-rows,]
dim(bank)
## [1] 41177    21

Duration is not used becuase it is not known how long a phone call will last before it is made. The month and day of the week columns are also deleted, because they are irelevant to the business question on hand.

bank$duration = NULL
bank$month=NULL
bank$day_of_week=NULL

Normalize the data.

norm= function(x){
  return((x-min(x))/ (max(x)- min(x)))}

for (i in 1:dim(bank)[2]){ bank[,i]=as.numeric(bank[,i])}

banknorm= data.frame((lapply(bank[,1:(dim(bank)[2]-1)], norm)))
banknorm$y= bank$y

hrl_rate=31.5
num_cust=1400000

In order to know how many customers to call a monte carlo simulation is run to capture customers that say yes from the .11 percent of the customers that actually say yes.

percent_called=1:100
people =c() #pectent of the 11% of customers who will buy
for(q in 1:100){
#Monte Carlo Simulation
l=c()
for (i in 1:250){
samp = sample(1:(dim(test)[1]), 1000)
df=test[samp,]
table(test$y)[[2]]/table(test$y)[[1]]
df1=df[order(df$pred,decreasing = T),]
dfcall= df1[1:(1000*q/100),]
l=append(l,(table(dfcall$y)[[2]]/table(df$y)[[2]]))
}
people=append(people, mean(l))
}
da=data.frame(percent_called, people)
plot(da)

#Same plot but with number of people on the yaxis rather than percent of percent. 
percent_called=1:100
people =c() #pectent of the 11% of customers who will buy
for(q in 1:100){
#Monte Carlo Simulation
l=c()
for (i in 1:250){
samp = sample(1:(dim(test)[1]), 1000)
df=test[samp,]
table(test$y)[[2]]/table(test$y)[[1]]
df1=df[order(df$pred,decreasing = T),]
dfcall= df1[1:(1000*q/100),]
l=append(l,(table(dfcall$y)[[2]]/table(df$y)[[2]]))
}
people=append(people, ((mean(l)*0.1126542)*num_cust) )
}
da=data.frame(percent_called, people)
plot(da)

Final Simulation using 18 percent of customers.

#Monte Carlo Simulation
l=c()
for (i in 1:1000){
samp = sample(1:(dim(test)[1]), 1000)
df=test[samp,]
table(test$y)[[2]]/table(test$y)[[1]]
df1=df[order(df$pred,decreasing = T),]
dfcall= df1[1:(1000*.18),]
l=append(l,(table(dfcall$y)[[2]]/table(df$y)[[2]]))
}


#cost without model
WM_cost_call=(num_cust/mean_duration)*hrl_rate
  
#cost with model
M_cost_call=((num_cust*.18)/mean_duration)*hrl_rate

#Savings
s=WM_cost_call-M_cost_call
s=formatC(s, format="d", big.mark=",")
lower = formatC(as.integer(((mean(l)-2*sd(l)))*(percent_yes*num_cust)), format="d", big.mark=",")
upper=formatC(as.integer((mean(l)+2*sd(l))*(percent_yes*num_cust)), format="d", big.mark=",")

#Certainty from monte carlo simulation
certainty= sum(l>(mean(l)-2*sd(l)) & l<(mean(l)+2*sd(l)))/length(l)

print(paste("Based on the simulation by calling 18% of the customers there is ",certainty*100,"%"," certainty that the model will get between ",lower," and " ,upper," customers saving $",s, sep=''))
## [1] "Based on the simulation by calling 18% of the customers there is 95.7% certainty that the model will get between 70,202 and 97,329 customers saving $5,735,675"
